"passed": true}, "short_span_min_tokens": {"details": {"min_tokens": 2, "token_count": 316}, "passed": true}}, "text": "Yemen's Crown Prince Fears His Position Will Be Undercut\nBy Returning Imam\n\nThe efforts of the Imam of Yemen to avoid visiting Egypt on his current journey home from Italy have heightened Crown Prince Badr's fears that the Imam is displeased by government changes instituted during his absence and will nullify them to the detriment of Badr's position. During the Imam's three-month absence the UAR assisted Badr with large military and technical missions to carry out reforms and changes which were intended to strengthen Badr's chances for succession against the feudal tribal chiefs who in the past have elected each new Imam.\n\nThe chief of the Egyptian military mission in Yemen has warned Cairo that the Imam, suspecting Badr and the Egyptians of plotting to circumscribe his authority, may curtail much of the Egyptian activity in Yemen upon his return.\n\nBadr's rivals in the Imam's entourage have attempted to exploit the Imam's suspicions. The UAR military mission is now training Badr's bodyguard in the use of heavy weapons acquired from the Soviet bloc, and is to assist Badr in expanding the unit to brigade size--about 3,000 men. The Egyptian Air Force mission is to be enlarged by eight pilots and eleven NCOs in early August,\n\nBadr had not initiated further domestic measures since he received word of the Imam's decision to return, and that Badr, fearing the Imam's anger, had released some of the persons he had imprisoned. The tribal chiefs had departed the northern capital of Sana to await the Imam's return, and had refused to provide Badr with the manpower required to enlarge his personal military force. Without such a force, Badr is probably not in a position to challenge his father successfully if the Imam were to weaken Badr's succession prospects.\n\nThe Imam's brother Prince Hasan, Badr's chief rival, will not accompany the Imam to Yemen 